I figure I will share my story in pieces on here when it seems right. This is my first vacation by myself since my divorce. No husband. No kids. No friends. Just me.

When struggling with the decision of divorce, I remember telling myself that I would not stay in my marriage because I was afraid to be alone. Or because I was afraid I couldn’t support myself and the kids. I would only stay if I felt completely sure that it’s where God was leading me and what I wanted. 

In the end, the decision wasn’t easy. And I knew it never would be. But one thing I’ve found is a comfort in not really ever being alone. I remember sitting alone in church one day when I arrived late, knowing that I wasn’t really alone even if it looked that way to everyone else in the room. I felt this assurance that the most important “person” was beside me. I remember so many moments, grieving and hurting, but showing up to work and to life knowing that most everyone had no clue how deeply I was hurting, but that was ok, because I still wasn’t alone. The “person” who mattered knew exactly how broken I felt and how much it took out of me to just survive the day. 

For a long time, I could only think small. One moment to the next. One decision at a time. I just felt the absence of a husband, a teammate, a best friend. But in 2023, I want to Think Big. I want to dream again. I want to focus on what I have, instead of what is missing. I want to appreciate every moment I get with God. With my kids. With myself. And imagine what else God may have in store.

#2023 #cheers

PSA - coparenting can look like this.

No, it’s not easy. We’ve had two hard conversations this week alone. Things that help us coparent peacefully:

1) instead of just having a conversation in the moment, ask the other person “when can we talk about [taxes, child support, scheduling]?” so that both people are prepared (emotionally and with research/advice if needed)
2) start a conversation with reminders of what’s important (“The reason I’m bringing up child support is not because I want to take money from you and leave you in a bad position financially but because I want to make sure we’re both taken care of financially”)
3) from a spiritual standpoint, I often think of “the battle is not against flesh and blood”. Neither of us is the bad guy. So I try to focus on remembering who the bad guy really is and then fighting against him together. 

#coparenting #easter #momlife #matching #family

i am and i will be

i’m not sure that i can adequately explain what this phrase means to me but i’ll try.

whenever someone has asked me if i’m ok the last few years, it’s felt like an impossible question to answer. because 1) clearly i’m not and because 2) maybe not so clearly, i am and because 3) i know that i will be.

i can be hurting and still be ok. i can be mourning and still be ok. i can not be ok and still be ok. and in that confusion of not okay okayness, i also knew that i WOULD BE ok- even if the moments felt impossibly difficult.

the beautiful thing is that i don’t have to stay where i am and who i am forever. i get to grow. and change. and hurt. and live. and love. and change again. and believe. and break. and be remade. 

i am and i will be.

and you are and you will be too.

#divorce #singlemoms #selflove #changeisgood #spirituality #christianblogger

New job(s). 

And you never know which “uniform” I’ll show up to work in on any given day. 😎

For the last few months, I feel like I’ve been busier than ever before in my life.

4 months ago I decided to start a program to get certified to teach Reformer Pilates. About 1 month in, I got offered a leadership position with @lifetime.life to take on a dual role leading the Membership Concierge department and the Facility Operations department. I knew it was going to be a big job but it felt like the right one. I told them, humbly but confidently, that I would be the hardest worker they could find. Because that’s who I am. 

So for the past few weeks I’ve been studying Pilates, attending 18 hour training weekends. Traveling to NJ to get trained in Facility Operations. Interviewing and hiring incredible new team members to fill my team. And, most importantly, finding a way to be the best and most present mom to my kids. 

I honestly don’t know how I stand sometimes by the end of the day. Someone said I’m like the energizer bunny. The truth is, I work hard when I need to and I take care of myself when I need to so I don’t burn out.

But here’s my super late post to say:
I got a promotion!
I passed my Pilates certification! 
I have the best team ever!
My babies are my favorite “job”!

And if I haven’t texted you back in 4 months, I’m sorry 😂

Divorce is kind of like this-

You can take a deep breath knowing that the unknown of separation will finally be over and you finally know (or at least you can choose) a definitive direction for tomorrow. Even if it’s not the direction you planned or hoped for, it’s a direction nonetheless. And with that direction comes the ability to breathe the deepest breath you’ve had in a while. Feeling excited to dream for the future and what it might hold, but also forgetting HOW to dream for the future because for so long tomorrow was out of your control.

At the same time, you find that the memories, the mourning, the sadness is like your own personal shadow. No matter how far you try to run, it is always right there with you. You can be enjoying an amazing moment, celebrating a new life when, out of nowhere, you’re brought right back to what happened. And again you mourn over what you thought your life would look like versus how it turned out. 

It’s not even that life is bad now. In fact, it’s very possible that life is better. In many ways. But it’s the loss of that dream. That hope. That moment on your wedding day when you thought you were the luckiest girl in the world. The loss of THAT that you are forced to face. 

I remember explaining the early stages to someone once like this-

Every day still has joy. And happiness. And love. And laughter. As if each day is a painter’s pallet filled with all of these beautiful amazing colors. But every single color has been tainted, ever so slightly. Every color is just a little off. It doesn’t ruin the beautiful picture, but you can’t escape the fact that it’s there…

So here’s to all of you who are going through something similar. Here’s to new days filled with light, while still being shadowed in dark. Here’s to finding beauty in the balance and surviving through those days (and thriving through those days) while you continue fighting your own invisible battles each moment.

#divorce #divorcesupport #singlemomsclub #realtalk

In the last two months, my sister was diagnosed with an auto-immune disease (one that can be genetic, but also stress-induced) and I, for the first time ever, got bronchitis and asthma. I know that’s not the end of the world and it’s very treatable, but then I found out my mom also suffered with asthma randomly as an adult in her young 30s due to the stress of being a divorced single mom, raising three kids and working full-time. It landed her in the hospital on several occasions. That information hit pretty close to home since that’s my reality right now and has been for a little while.

Needless to say, I’ve been thinking about what self-care means a little extra lately.

I’ve always been a hard worker. I like to be busy. I like to be active. I enjoy helping people. But I started thinking even more about setting boundaries that are good for my body, even if mentally I think I can handle more. I started cutting dairy and extra sugars out because I realized my body feels better without them. I’ve been trying to go to sleep earlier (which means I basically don’t watch tv or read books anymore because late nights used to be my time for that). I’m trying to drink more water and have added in an amino recovery drink that I have at least once a day.

What do y’all do to set boundaries and take care of yourself?

I just took a walk down memory lane via old photos. Needless to say there were tears. But is anyone surprised? Probably not.

A lot has changed between these two pictures.
-I had another baby.
-I got divorced.
-I moved.
-I changed careers.
-I lost friends.
-I found friends.
-I lost myself.
-I found myself.

But life goes on. No matter what is going on in your life, remember that it will not stop moving for you. Don’t miss out on the space between the photos. Don’t miss out on the journey. The journey is often hard, but it is where the future beauty is created.

I cried looking at these photos and seeing the void behind me now. But there is so much in that blank space. So much fight. So much strength. So much perseverance. So many mistakes. So many prayers. So much love. So much growth. And there is God. Who never left and who never leaves.

#divorce #singlemoms #mamasgirl #minime #thenandnow #divorceblog

nyc getaway

this will be the first year that I’m not with my kids on Christmas. I’m sure I’ll cry on Christmas morning just from missing them. BUT I’ve also decided to make the most of it. pre-Christmas getaway to nyc and then when they get back in the 28th, we’re going to just pretend it’s Christmas again. this year is a year of building new traditions out of a less than ideal situation. finding the good. making it special.

first christmas without kids

yesterday I dropped the kids off at the airport to go to FL for Christmas. I cried last night as soon as I got home to an empty house. I cried this morning when I walked into the living room with everyone else except my babies. I cried after I got off FT. I cried when I opened gifts/cards the kids had surprised me with. I cried when I opened this gift from my sister @mrsjenibrahim. I cried reading a card from @tiffanynoellechacon (and seeing her whole stack of books that I can’t wait to read!) I cried when I didn’t fill their stockings and theirs hung empty when all the others were stuffed full. I cried watching my nieces and nephews open their gifts, imagining my kids’ joy as they open their presents. 

I started writing more about how I laughed too. About the moments that were good. And they were true. But I erased it because sometimes it’s ok for moments to just be hard. This year, my family watched me cry. A few times. But this is just me this year. And that’s ok.

#singlemomlife #divorced #divorceblog #coparenting #christmas

2024 Theme: “Make Lemonade”

2019 - “Laugh at the days to come”
2022 - “See the good”
2023 - “Dream Big”

Every time I set a New Years Resolution (really more of a focus), God moves in a big way. He moves by challenging me.

In 2019, when I thought of “laugh at the days to come”, 10 days later my marriage started falling apart. 

In 2022, when I thought of “see the good”, there was plenty of “hard” that wanted to steal my focus.

In 2023, when I thought of “dream big”, I was given an opportunity to take a huge promotion at work, get certified in pilates and be challenged beyond what I could’ve ever imagined.

In 2024, I want to focus on taking those life lemons and makin’ some lemonade.

Last night, red threw up in his bed. When I told Harper that would be changing our plans today she was so upset and told me that she made a whole list for NYE and how sad she was that none of that would be happening now. She said she’s never felt so small… I told her about my New Years theme and we agreed to make lemonade today. And we did.

2024, I don’t know what’s coming. I don’t know what hardships you might bring. I don’t know what miracles you might bring. I don’t know how you will challenge me to grow. But I’m excited to make lemonade with you. 🍋 🍋
first snow in a WHILE. ❄️
